[general]
Write clean, idiomatic code.
Prefer explicit error handling over silent failures.
Add comments for complex logic, not obvious code.
Follow the principle of least surprise.

[go]
Use table-driven tests with descriptive test names.
Return errors as the last return value.
Use context.Context for cancellation in long operations.
Prefer interfaces over concrete types in function params.

[typescript]
Use strict TypeScript — no 'any' types without comment.
Prefer functional patterns (map/filter/reduce).
Use async/await over Promise chains.
Export types alongside implementations.

[python]
Follow PEP 8 style guide.
Use type hints for all function signatures.
Write docstrings for public functions.
Prefer list comprehensions for simple transforms.

[testing]
Write tests before implementation (TDD).
Aim for 80% code coverage minimum.
Test edge cases: empty inputs, nulls, large values.
Use descriptive test names: "TestHandleAuth_ReturnsError_WhenTokenExpired"

[agent]
Before making changes, explain what you plan to do.
Make small, atomic changes. One concern per commit.
Never delete code without understanding why it exists.
Check for existing tests before writing new ones.

[review]
Flag any hardcoded secrets, credentials, or tokens.
Check for SQL injection, XSS, and CSRF vulnerabilities.
Identify missing error handling.
Note performance bottlenecks (N+1 queries, missing indexes).
